  <body>
    <div rend="parallel">
      <lg xml:id="TolE0482">
<l>uyirum puḷḷiyu miṟuti yākik</l>
<l>kuṟippiṉum paṇpiṉu micaiyiṉun tōṉṟi</l>
<l>neṟippaṭa vārāk kuṟaiccoṟ kiḷaviyu</l>
<l>muyartiṇai yaḵṟiṇai yāyiru maruṅki</l>
<l>ṉaimpā laṟiyum paṇputoku moḻiyum</l>
<l>tammiyal kiḷappiṟ ṟammuṟ ṟāmvarūu</l>
<l>meṇṇiṉ ṟokuti yuḷappaṭap piṟavu</l>
<l>maṉṉavai yellā maruviṉ pāttiya</l>
<l>puṇariya ṉilaiyiṭai yuṇarat tōṉṟā</l>
      </lg>
      <lg xml:lang="en">
<l>The ' defective ' words [and] expressions ending in vowel or con-</l>
<l>sonant [and] denoting suggestion, quality [or] sound<note place="foot">The term is <foreign xml:lang="ta">kuṟaiccol ;</foreign> it is
          interpreted by <foreign xml:lang="ta">Iḷampūraṇar</foreign> and <foreign xml:lang="ta">
          Nacciṉārkkiṉiyar</foreign> as <foreign xml:lang="ta">uriccol</foreign> ' words of quality
          ', corresponding roughly to our category of adjectives; but the instances given in the
          commentaries, and what the text says about e.g. ' sound ' (<foreign xml:lang="ta">icai)</foreign>
          indicate that it also covers, partly at least, adverbs and various particles,
          onomatopoetic words, etc. These words cannot be isolated and discussed as separate units;
          they occur as bound forms, and manifest irre<corr>i</corr>gularities in morphonemic
          alterations.</note>, the ex-</l>
<l>pressions denoting the five genders under [the more general dis-</l>
<l>tinction into] high gender and no-gender, [and forming the first</l>
<l>member of] <foreign xml:lang="ta">paṇputtokai</foreign><note place="foot"><foreign xml:lang="ta">Paṇputtokai</foreign> is an attribute-head
          construction of compound-like nature ; it is stated here that the first part is supposed
          to be a noun ' agreeing ' in gender with the second part; such is the case in various
          Indo-European languages, including Sanskrit, but not in Dravidian as a rule; it is not
          clear why it is mentioned in this aphorism.</note>, the adjective participles [of the
          type]</l>
<l><foreign xml:lang="ta">ceyyum</foreign> and <foreign xml:lang="ta">ceyta</foreign> when they form the first member of a <foreign xml:lang="ta">viṇaittokai</foreign><note place="foot"><foreign xml:lang="ta">Viṉaittokai</foreign> is a compound-like
          construction involving a verb-root and a noun, wherein the verb-root functions as a
          relative or adjectival participle; according to this aphorism, the compound-like e.g. <foreign xml:lang="ta">kolyānai</foreign> ' killing-elephant ' - can in fact be interpreted
          either as <foreign xml:lang="ta">kollumyāṉai</foreign> ' the elephant which kills
          (habitually) ', or as <foreign xml:lang="ta">koṉṟayāṉai</foreign> ' the elephant which did
          kill '; hence the specific meaning depends on the context.</note>,</l>
<l>and words denoting number preceding the same words - these</l>
<l>and all similar words have to be determined from usage and cannot</l>
<l>be clearly discussed as to their formation in the chapter on joining</l>
<l>words.<note place="foot">The fourth category concerns compounds of numerals preceding other
          numerals, which are so transformed that it is difficult to recognize the basic forms, as
          e.g. <foreign xml:lang="ta">pattu+pattu&gt;pappattu.</foreign> There may be other such
          difficult combinations; they are all considered as <foreign xml:lang="ta">marū</foreign>
          or fused terms which are beyond recognition as two different words. Hence their
          morphophonemic combinations cannot be traced and explained in terms of the rules stated
          above in the chapters on <foreign xml:lang="ta">sandhi.</foreign></note></l>
      </lg>
